ame <i>Maheu</i> (see   Matthew  ). Alternative derivation of Middle English <i>Mawe</i> from an Old English personal name <i>Māwa</i> is theoretically possible in northern England. Compare   Mew  .","English (Yorkshire and Lincolnshire): occasionally a variant of   Mowe  .","English (Yorkshire and Lincolnshire): topographic name meaning either ‘(dweller by) the meadow’, from an otherwise unrecorded Middle English word <i>mawe</i>, <i>mowe</i> ‘meadow’ (attested in the second element of the Old English placename Dunmow, Essex), or ‘(dweller by) the wet hollow’, from Middle English <i>mawe</i> ‘stomach’ (Old English <i>maga</i>) used topographically to denote a depression which collects water. See also   Mowe  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moment","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): variant of <b>Mawman</b>, with excrescent <i>-t</i> and re-spelt through folk etymology as though identical with the word <i>moment</i>. <b>Mawman</b> is probably an occupational name from an unrecorded Middle English <i>Mawman</i> ‘servant of <i>Maw</i>’ (a pet form of <i>Matthew</i>, see   Maw  )."]},{"name":"Mow","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Mowe</b>, see   Maw   1–3.","Americanized form of French   Mau  , <b>Maux</b>,   Meaux   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname. Compare   Moe  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 毛, see   Mao   1."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."]},{"name":"Mawson","meanings":["English:","patronymic from   Maw   1.","metronymic from a form of   Maude   2."]},{"name":"Mew","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>mew</i> ‘seagull’ (Old English <i>mǣw</i>, <i>mēaw</i>). Compare   Maw   3.","English (of Norman origin): metonymic occupational name or nickname from Old French <i>mue</i> ‘mew’, possibly denoting someone employed at a mew, i.e. a cage or set of cages for hawks.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 苗 and 繆 (see   Miao   1 and 2)."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Maw was born in 1504, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of John Maw and Mary Elizabeth Thompson. She married Thomas Carwythan about 1525, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1540, in Devon, England."},"et":{"1504–after 1540":"1504–pärast 1540","1504–1540":"1504–1540","1502–Male":"1502–Surnud","1529–1590":"1529–1590","1475–Male":"1475–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1502":"1502","about 1525":"umbes 1525","about 1503":"umbes 1503","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1529":"1529","after 1540":"pärast 1540","1590":"1590","1504":"1504","Smallhall, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1504–after 1540":"1504–1540 jälkeen","1504–1540":"1504–1540","1502–Male":"1502–Kuollut","1529–1590":"1529–1590","1475–Male":"1475–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1502":"1502","about 1525":"noin 1525","about 1503":"noin 1503","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1529":"1529","after 1540":"1540 jälkeen","1590":"1590","1504":"1504","Smallhall, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"1504–after 1540":"1504–après 1540","1504–1540":"1504–1540","1502–Male":"1502–Décédé","1529–1590":"1529–1590","1475–Male":"1475–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1502":"1502","about 1525":"environ 1525","about 1503":"environ 1503","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1529":"1529","after 1540":"après 1540","1590":"1590","1504":"1504","Smallhall, Cornwall, England":"Cornouailles, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre","Cornwall, England":"Cornouailles, Angleterre","Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Alice 